Chapter 2: Mathematical Preliminaries

This chapter establishes the notation, definitions, and foundational results required for the subsequent development, with expanded references to the key theorems employed.

2.1 Differential Geometry of Dynamical Systems

Definition 2.1 (Smooth Manifold). A d-dimensional C^k manifold \mathcal{M} is a topological space that is locally homeomorphic to \mathbb{R}^d with C^k smooth transition maps between coordinate charts.

Definition 2.2 (Tangent Space). Let \mathcal{M} be a smooth manifold and p \in \mathcal{M}. The tangent space T_p \mathcal{M} is the vector space of all derivations at p.

Definition 2.3 (Dynamical System). A discrete-time dynamical system on a manifold \mathcal{M} is a smooth map \Phi: \mathcal{M} \to \mathcal{M}. The trajectory of a point x_0 is the sequence x_{t+1} = \Phi(x_t).

Definition 2.4 (Invariant Manifold). A submanifold \Lambda \subset \mathcal{M} is invariant under \Phi if \Phi(\Lambda) \subseteq \Lambda.

2.2 Normally Hyperbolic Invariant Manifolds (NHIMs)

We follow the classical formulation of Fenichel (1971, 1979) and Hirsch, Pugh, and Shub (1977), as well as the comprehensive treatments by Wiggins (1994) and Eldering (2013).

Definition 2.5 (Normal Hyperbolicity). Let \Phi: \mathcal{M} \to \mathcal{M} be a C^r diffeomorphism (r \ge 1). A compact invariant submanifold \Lambda \subset \mathcal{M} is normally hyperbolic if there exists a continuous D\Phi-invariant splitting of the tangent bundle over \Lambda:

T_\Lambda \mathcal{M} = E^s \oplus T\Lambda \oplus E^u

and constants 0 < \mu_- \le \mu_+ < 1 and 0 < \lambda_- \le \lambda_+ < \infty such that:

1. For all x \in \Lambda and v \in E^s_x, \|D\Phi_x^k v\| \le C (\mu_+)^k \|v\| for k \ge 0.
2. For all x \in \Lambda and v \in E^u_x, \|D\Phi_x^{-k} v\| \le C (\lambda_-)^{-k} \|v\| for k \ge 0.
3. The rates satisfy \mu_+ < \rho(T_x\Lambda) \le \tilde{\rho}(T_x\Lambda) < \lambda_-, where \rho and \tilde{\rho} denote the minimum and maximum norms on T\Lambda.

In our setting, the unstable bundle E^u is empty, simplifying the definition to a spectral gap between tangential and normal contraction rates.

Theorem 2.1 (Fenichel Persistence Theorem). Let \Lambda be a compact, normally hyperbolic invariant manifold for a C^r diffeomorphism \Phi. Then there exists \varepsilon > 0 such that for any C^r diffeomorphism \tilde{\Phi} with \|\Phi - \tilde{\Phi}\|_{C^1} < \varepsilon, there exists a unique C^r manifold \tilde{\Lambda} invariant under \tilde{\Phi} and C^1-close to \Lambda. Moreover, \tilde{\Lambda} is normally hyperbolic.

References: Fenichel (1971, 1979); Hirsch, Pugh, & Shub (1977); Wiggins (1994); Eldering (2013).

Theorem 2.2 (Hadamard Graph Transform). The proof of persistence is constructive and relies on the Graph Transform operator \Gamma acting on the space of Lipschitz sections h: \Lambda \to E^s. Under the spectral gap condition, \Gamma is a contraction mapping, and its unique fixed point defines the perturbed invariant manifold.

2.3 Information Theory

Definition 2.6 (Mutual Information). For continuous random variables X, Y with joint density p(x,y):

I(X; Y) = \int \int p(x,y) \log \frac{p(x,y)}{p(x)p(y)} \, dx \, dy

Definition 2.7 (Conditional Mutual Information).

I(X; Y \mid Z) = \mathbb{E}_{p(z)}[I(X; Y \mid Z=z)]

Theorem 2.8 (Chain Rule). I(X; Y, Z) = I(X; Z) + I(X; Y \mid Z).

Definition 2.9 (CLUB Estimator — Cheng et al., 2020). For a variational approximation q_\psi(y|x):

I_{\text{CLUB}}(X; Y) = \mathbb{E}_{p(x,y)}[\log q_\psi(y|x)] - \mathbb{E}_{p(x)p(y)}[\log q_\psi(y|x)] \ge I(X; Y)

Lemma 2.10 (Conditional CLUB). Extending to conditional MI:

I_{\text{CLUB}}(X; Y \mid Z) = \mathbb{E}_{p(x,y,z)}[\log q_\psi(y|x,z)] - \mathbb{E}_{p(z)p(x)p(y)}[\log q_\psi(y|x,z)]

Reference: Cheng et al. (2020), "CLUB: A Contrastive Log-ratio Upper Bound of Mutual Information," ICML.

2.4 Structured State-Space Models (SSM)

Definition 2.11 (Selective SSM — Mamba). A selective SSM layer maps input \mathbf{u}_t \in \mathbb{R}^D to output \mathbf{y}_t \in \mathbb{R}^D via:

\mathbf{h}_t = \bar{\mathbf{A}}_t \mathbf{h}_{t-1} + \bar{\mathbf{B}}_t \mathbf{u}_t, \quad \mathbf{y}_t = \mathbf{C}_t \mathbf{h}_t

with input-dependent parameters:

\bar{\mathbf{A}}_t = \exp(\Delta_t \cdot \mathbf{A}), \quad \bar{\mathbf{B}}_t = (\Delta_t \mathbf{A})^{-1}(\exp(\Delta_t \mathbf{A}) - \mathbf{I}) \Delta_t \mathbf{B}_t

\Delta_t = \text{softplus}(W_\Delta \mathbf{u}_t + b_\Delta), \quad \mathbf{B}_t = W_B \mathbf{u}_t, \quad \mathbf{C}_t = W_C \mathbf{u}_t

Reference: Gu & Dao (2023), "Mamba: Linear-Time Sequence Modeling with Selective State Spaces."

Lemma 2.12 (Spectral Bound). If \mathbf{A} is diagonal with \text{Re}(\lambda_i) \le 0 and \Delta_t > 0, then |\lambda_i(\bar{\mathbf{A}}_t)| = \exp(\Delta_t \text{Re}(\lambda_i)) \le 1.

2.5 Input-to-State Stability (ISS)

Definition 2.13 (ISS — Sontag, 1989). A system \mathbf{z}_{t+1} = F(\mathbf{z}_t, \mathbf{u}_t) is Input-to-State Stable if there exist a \mathcal{KL}-function \beta and a \mathcal{K}-function \gamma such that:

\|\mathbf{z}_t\| \le \beta(\|\mathbf{z}_0\|, t) + \gamma\left(\sup_{0 \le \tau \le t} \|\mathbf{u}_\tau\|\right)

Reference: Sontag (1989), "Smooth stabilization implies coprime factorization," IEEE TAC; Jiang & Wang (2001) for discrete-time ISS.

Lemma 2.14 (Discrete-Time Gronwall Inequality). For nonnegative sequences \{x_t\}, \{a_t\}, \{b_t\} satisfying x_t \le a_t + \sum_{k=0}^{t-1} b_k x_k, we have:

x_t \le a_t + \sum_{k=0}^{t-1} a_k b_k \prod_{j=k+1}^{t-1} (1 + b_j)

2.6 Fisher Information and Log-Sobolev Inequalities

Definition 2.15 (Fisher Information Matrix). For a parametric family of densities p_\theta(x), the Fisher Information Matrix is:

\mathcal{F}(\theta) = \mathbb{E}_{p_\theta}\left[ \nabla_\theta \log p_\theta(x) \, \nabla_\theta \log p_\theta(x)^\top \right]

Definition 2.16 (Log-Sobolev Inequality). A probability measure \mu satisfies a log-Sobolev inequality with constant C > 0 if for all smooth functions f:

\text{Ent}_\mu(f^2) \le 2C \mathbb{E}_\mu[\|\nabla f\|^2]

where \text{Ent}_\mu(g) = \mathbb{E}_\mu[g \log g] - \mathbb{E}_\mu[g] \log \mathbb{E}_\mu[g].

Reference: Otto & Villani (2000); Bakry, Gentil, & Ledoux (2014).

