Chapter 4: Stability and Contractivity of the SSM Core

This chapter establishes rigorous stability guarantees for the LDVS core parameterized as a selective SSM. We provide a complete proof of Input-to-State Stability (ISS) using the discrete-time Gronwall inequality.

4.1 Contractive Constraints

Definition 4.1 (Contraction). A map F: \mathcal{X} \to \mathcal{X} is a contraction with factor \rho \in [0,1) if \|F(\mathbf{x}) - F(\mathbf{y})\| \le \rho \|\mathbf{x} - \mathbf{y}\| for all \mathbf{x}, \mathbf{y}.

Lemma 4.1 (SSM Contraction). The SSM update \mathbf{z}_t = \bar{\mathbf{A}}_t \mathbf{z}_{t-1} + \bar{\mathbf{B}}_t \mathbf{u}_t is a contraction in \mathbf{z} if \|\bar{\mathbf{A}}_t\|_2 \le 1 - \delta for some \delta > 0.

Proof. For any \mathbf{z}, \mathbf{z}':

\|F(\mathbf{z}) - F(\mathbf{z}')\| = \|\bar{\mathbf{A}}_t (\mathbf{z} - \mathbf{z}')\| \le \|\bar{\mathbf{A}}_t\|_2 \|\mathbf{z} - \mathbf{z}'\| \le (1-\delta) \|\mathbf{z} - \mathbf{z}'\|

∎

4.2 Bounded State Trajectories via ISS

Theorem 4.2 (Input-to-State Stability). Assume \|\bar{\mathbf{A}}_t\|_2 \le 1 - \delta with \delta \in (0,1], and \|\bar{\mathbf{B}}_t \mathbf{u}_t\|_2 \le M for all t. Then for any initial state \mathbf{z}_0:

\|\mathbf{z}_t\|_2 \le (1-\delta)^t \|\mathbf{z}_0\|_2 + \frac{M}{\delta}

In particular, \limsup_{t \to \infty} \|\mathbf{z}_t\|_2 \le M/\delta < \infty. This satisfies the ISS definition with \beta(r, t) = (1-\delta)^t r and \gamma(r) = M(r)/\delta, where M(r) bounds \|\bar{\mathbf{B}}_t \mathbf{u}_t\|_2 when \|\mathbf{u}_t\| \le r.

Proof. By induction:

\|\mathbf{z}_t\|_2 \le (1-\delta)\|\mathbf{z}_{t-1}\|_2 + M

Unrolling yields:

\|\mathbf{z}_t\|_2 \le (1-\delta)^t \|\mathbf{z}_0\|_2 + M \sum_{i=0}^{t-1} (1-\delta)^i = (1-\delta)^t \|\mathbf{z}_0\|_2 + M \frac{1 - (1-\delta)^t}{\delta}

Taking the limit gives M/\delta. ∎

Corollary 4.3 (Discrete-Time Gronwall Proof). The same bound can be derived via the discrete-time Gronwall inequality. Define x_t = \|\mathbf{z}_t\|. Then:

x_t \le (1-\delta) x_{t-1} + M \le (1-\delta)^t x_0 + \sum_{k=0}^{t-1} M (1-\delta)^{t-1-k}

The geometric series converges to M/\delta, establishing uniform boundedness regardless of sequence length.

4.3 Spectral Gap for Factorized SSM

Assumption 4.4 (Block-Diagonal SSM). The SSM transition matrix \bar{\mathbf{A}}_t has the block structure:

\bar{\mathbf{A}}_t = \begin{bmatrix}
\bar{\mathbf{A}}_c & \mathbf{0} & \mathbf{0} & \mathbf{0} \\
\bar{\mathbf{A}}_{pc} & \bar{\mathbf{A}}_p & \mathbf{0} & \mathbf{0} \\
\mathbf{0} & \mathbf{0} & \bar{\mathbf{A}}_s & \mathbf{0} \\
\bar{\mathbf{A}}_{\epsilon c} & \bar{\mathbf{A}}_{\epsilon p} & \bar{\mathbf{A}}_{\epsilon s} & \bar{\mathbf{A}}_\epsilon
\end{bmatrix}

Theorem 4.5 (Spectral Radius of Block Triangular Matrix).

\rho(\bar{\mathbf{A}}_t) = \max\{\rho(\bar{\mathbf{A}}_c), \rho(\bar{\mathbf{A}}_p), \rho(\bar{\mathbf{A}}_s), \rho(\bar{\mathbf{A}}_\epsilon)\}

Proof. The eigenvalues of a block triangular matrix are the union of the eigenvalues of its diagonal blocks. ∎

Corollary 4.6 (Independent Stability Control). The contractivity of each factor can be controlled independently by designing the corresponding diagonal block. In particular:

· \rho(\bar{\mathbf{A}}_s) \approx 1 to maintain stable speaker identity.
· \rho(\bar{\mathbf{A}}_c), \rho(\bar{\mathbf{A}}_p) \le 1 - \delta for content and prosody evolution.
· \rho(\bar{\mathbf{A}}_\epsilon) \le \nu < \min(\rho_c, \rho_p) to satisfy the NHIM spectral gap.

4.4 Lyapunov Stability

Proposition 4.7 (Quadratic Lyapunov Function). If \|\bar{\mathbf{A}}_t\|_2 \le 1 - \delta, then V(\mathbf{z}) = \|\mathbf{z}\|_2^2 satisfies:

V(F(\mathbf{z})) - V(\mathbf{z}) \le -\delta(2-\delta) V(\mathbf{z}) \le -\delta V(\mathbf{z})

for the unforced system (\mathbf{u}_t = \mathbf{0}).

Proof. V(F(\mathbf{z})) = \|\bar{\mathbf{A}}_t \mathbf{z}\|_2^2 \le (1-\delta)^2 V(\mathbf{z}). Thus V(F(\mathbf{z})) - V(\mathbf{z}) \le ((1-\delta)^2 - 1)V(\mathbf{z}) = -\delta(2-\delta)V(\mathbf{z}) \le -\delta V(\mathbf{z}). ∎

This Lyapunov function guarantees global exponential stability of the origin for the unforced system, and ISS for the forced system.

