Chapter 5: Information-Theoretic Bounds on Disentanglement Leakage

This chapter establishes quantitative relationships between the perturbation magnitude \delta and the mutual information leakage. We leverage the Fisher Information Metric and log-Sobolev inequalities to derive an \mathcal{O}(\delta^2) bound.

5.1 Data Processing Inequality

Lemma 5.1 (Data Processing). For any Markov chain X \to Y \to Z, I(X; Z) \le I(X; Y).

In our setting, deterministic contractive dynamics without input satisfy I(\mathbf{z}_t; \mathbf{z}_{t+k}) \le \rho^k H(\mathbf{z}_t), showing information monotonic decay.

5.2 Fisher Information and Mutual Information Relationship

Theorem 5.2 (MI Expansion via Fisher Metric). Let p_\theta be a parametric family of probability densities with parameter \theta. For small perturbations \Delta\theta, the mutual information expands as:

I(p_{\theta + \Delta\theta}; p_\theta) = \frac{1}{2} \Delta\theta^\top \mathcal{F}(\theta) \Delta\theta + \mathcal{O}(\|\Delta\theta\|^3)

where \mathcal{F}(\theta) is the Fisher Information Matrix.

Proof. This follows from the Taylor expansion of the KL divergence, noting that D_{\text{KL}}(p_\theta \| p_{\theta + \Delta\theta}) \approx \frac{1}{2} \Delta\theta^\top \mathcal{F}(\theta) \Delta\theta. For small perturbations, MI and KL divergence are related up to second order. ∎

5.3 Perturbation Bound via Log-Sobolev Inequality

Theorem 5.3 (Log-Sobolev Bound on MI Leakage). Assume the stationary distribution of the unperturbed system satisfies a log-Sobolev inequality with constant C_{\text{LSI}}. Let the perturbation magnitude be \delta = \|J_{\text{off-diag}}\|_2. Then the mutual information leakage is bounded by:

I(\mathbf{c}_t; \mathbf{p}_t \mid \mathbf{s}) \le C_{\text{LSI}} \cdot \delta^2 \cdot \frac{1}{1 - \rho_{\max}^2} + \mathcal{O}(\delta^3)

where \rho_{\max} = \max(\rho_c, \rho_p).

Proof Sketch. The perturbation \delta induces a change in the stationary measure p_\delta = p_0 + \delta p' + \frac{1}{2}\delta^2 p'' + \dots. Using the log-Sobolev inequality, we can bound the Fisher information of the perturbation. The contraction property ensures that the effect of the perturbation decays geometrically. Summing the geometric series yields the 1/(1-\rho_{\max}^2) factor. A rigorous proof follows Otto & Villani (2000) and the Bakry-Émery criterion. ∎

Corollary 5.4 (Steady-State Disentanglement). As t \to \infty:

\limsup_{t \to \infty} I(\mathbf{c}_t; \mathbf{p}_t \mid \mathbf{s}) \le C \cdot \delta^2

Thus the asymptotic information leakage is proportional to the square of the coupling strength.

5.4 Conditional CLUB Implementation

The conditional CLUB estimator is trained adversarially:

\mathcal{L}_{\text{CMI}} = \mathbb{E}_{p(\mathbf{c},\mathbf{p},\mathbf{s})}[\log q_\psi(\mathbf{s}|\mathbf{p},\mathbf{c})] - \mathbb{E}_{p(\mathbf{c})p(\mathbf{p})p(\mathbf{s})}[\log q_\psi(\mathbf{s}|\mathbf{p},\mathbf{c})]

The variational network q_\psi is a 3-layer MLP outputting the mean and log-variance of a Gaussian over \mathbf{s}. The gap I_{\text{CLUB}} - I equals \mathbb{E}[D_{\text{KL}}(p(\mathbf{s}|\mathbf{p},\mathbf{c}) \parallel q_\psi(\mathbf{s}|\mathbf{p},\mathbf{c}))], which can be minimized by maximizing the likelihood.

5.5 Orthogonality and Linear Correlation

Proposition 5.5 (Orthogonality Implies Zero Gaussian MI). If \mathcal{C} \perp \mathcal{P} and the latent variables are jointly Gaussian, then I(\mathbf{c}; \mathbf{p}) = 0.

Proof. For zero-mean Gaussians, I(\mathbf{c}; \mathbf{p}) = -\frac{1}{2}\log\det(I - \Sigma_{cp}\Sigma_p^{-1}\Sigma_{pc}\Sigma_c^{-1}). Orthogonal subspaces imply \Sigma_{cp} = 0, giving zero MI. ∎

This justifies the orthogonal projection penalty \mathcal{L}_{\text{orth}} as a tractable proxy for MI minimization.

