Appendix A: Complete Mathematical Background

This appendix provides a self-contained exposition of the mathematical foundations required for the UMVIS framework. It is intended as a reference for readers who require deeper background in differential geometry, dynamical systems theory, control theory, and information theory.

A.1 Differential Geometry of Dynamical Systems

A.1.1 Smooth Manifolds

Definition A.1 (Topological Manifold). A topological space \mathcal{M} is a d-dimensional topological manifold if it is Hausdorff, second-countable, and locally homeomorphic to \mathbb{R}^d.

Definition A.2 (Smooth Manifold). A d-dimensional C^k manifold is a topological manifold \mathcal{M} together with a maximal C^k-atlas: a collection of charts \{(U_\alpha, \varphi_\alpha)\} where U_\alpha \subset \mathcal{M} are open sets covering \mathcal{M}, \varphi_\alpha: U_\alpha \to \mathbb{R}^d are homeomorphisms, and for any \alpha, \beta with U_\alpha \cap U_\beta \neq \emptyset, the transition map \varphi_\beta \circ \varphi_\alpha^{-1}: \varphi_\alpha(U_\alpha \cap U_\beta) \to \varphi_\beta(U_\alpha \cap U_\beta) is C^k.

Definition A.3 (Tangent Space). Let \mathcal{M} be a smooth manifold and p \in \mathcal{M}. A tangent vector at p is an equivalence class of curves \gamma: (-\epsilon, \epsilon) \to \mathcal{M} with \gamma(0) = p, where two curves are equivalent if they have the same derivative in any coordinate chart. The set of all tangent vectors at p forms a vector space T_p\mathcal{M} of dimension d, called the tangent space.

Definition A.4 (Tangent Bundle). The tangent bundle T\mathcal{M} is the disjoint union of all tangent spaces: T\mathcal{M} = \bigsqcup_{p \in \mathcal{M}} T_p\mathcal{M}, endowed with a natural smooth manifold structure of dimension 2d.

Definition A.5 (Vector Field). A vector field X on \mathcal{M} is a smooth section of the tangent bundle, i.e., a smooth map X: \mathcal{M} \to T\mathcal{M} such that X(p) \in T_p\mathcal{M} for all p.

Definition A.6 (Flow). A flow on \mathcal{M} is a smooth map \Phi: \mathbb{R} \times \mathcal{M} \to \mathcal{M} satisfying \Phi(0, p) = p and \Phi(t, \Phi(s, p)) = \Phi(t+s, p). For discrete-time systems, we consider a diffeomorphism \Phi: \mathcal{M} \to \mathcal{M}.

A.1.2 Riemannian Geometry

Definition A.7 (Riemannian Metric). A Riemannian metric g on \mathcal{M} is a smooth assignment of an inner product g_p: T_p\mathcal{M} \times T_p\mathcal{M} \to \mathbb{R} at each point p. The pair (\mathcal{M}, g) is a Riemannian manifold.

Definition A.8 (Geodesic Distance). The distance between two points p, q \in \mathcal{M} is defined as

d_g(p, q) = \inf_{\gamma} \int_0^1 \sqrt{g_{\gamma(t)}(\dot{\gamma}(t), \dot{\gamma}(t))} \, dt

where the infimum is over all piecewise smooth curves \gamma with \gamma(0) = p and \gamma(1) = q.

Definition A.9 (Exponential Map). For p \in \mathcal{M} and v \in T_p\mathcal{M}, let \gamma_v be the unique geodesic with \gamma_v(0) = p and \dot{\gamma}_v(0) = v. The exponential map is \exp_p(v) = \gamma_v(1), defined for sufficiently small v.

A.1.3 Submanifolds

Definition A.10 (Immersed Submanifold). A subset \mathcal{N} \subset \mathcal{M} is an immersed submanifold if there exists an injective immersion \iota: \mathcal{N} \to \mathcal{M} whose image is \mathcal{N}.

Definition A.11 (Embedded Submanifold). An embedded submanifold is an immersed submanifold where the topology on \mathcal{N} coincides with the subspace topology from \mathcal{M}.

Definition A.12 (Invariant Manifold). A submanifold \Lambda \subset \mathcal{M} is invariant under a diffeomorphism \Phi: \mathcal{M} \to \mathcal{M} if \Phi(\Lambda) \subseteq \Lambda.

A.2 Normally Hyperbolic Invariant Manifold Theory

This section provides a detailed exposition of NHIM theory, following the seminal works of Fenichel (1971, 1979), Hirsch, Pugh, and Shub (1977), and the modern treatment by Wiggins (1994) and Eldering (2013).

A.2.1 Linear Theory: Exponential Dichotomies

Definition A.13 (Exponential Dichotomy). Let A: \mathbb{Z} \to \mathcal{L}(\mathbb{R}^n) be a sequence of invertible linear operators. The linear difference equation x_{k+1} = A_k x_k admits an exponential dichotomy if there exist projections P_k^s, P_k^u such that P_k^s + P_k^u = I, A_k P_k^{s,u} = P_{k+1}^{s,u} A_k, and constants K > 0, 0 < \alpha < 1 < \beta with:

\|A_{k-1} \cdots A_m P_m^s\| \le K \alpha^{k-m}, \quad k \ge m

\|A_k^{-1} \cdots A_{m-1}^{-1} P_m^u\| \le K \beta^{-(m-k)}, \quad k \le m

Definition A.14 (Normal Hyperbolicity — Linear). The invariant manifold \Lambda is normally hyperbolic if the linearized dynamics along \Lambda admit an exponential dichotomy with the tangential part having growth rates strictly between the stable and unstable rates.

A.2.2 Fenichel's Theorems

Theorem A.1 (Fenichel's First Theorem — Persistence). Let \Phi be a C^r diffeomorphism (r \ge 1) with a compact normally hyperbolic invariant manifold \Lambda. Then there exists \varepsilon > 0 such that for any C^r diffeomorphism \tilde{\Phi} with \|\Phi - \tilde{\Phi}\|_{C^1} < \varepsilon, there exists a unique C^r manifold \tilde{\Lambda} invariant under \tilde{\Phi} and C^1-close to \Lambda.

Theorem A.2 (Fenichel's Second Theorem — Stable and Unstable Manifolds). Under the same conditions, there exist C^r stable and unstable manifolds W^s(\Lambda) and W^u(\Lambda) that are invariant and fiber over \Lambda.

Theorem A.3 (Fenichel's Third Theorem — Foliation). The stable and unstable manifolds are foliated by invariant fibers that are C^r in the base point and C^{r-1} in the fiber direction.

A.2.3 The Hadamard Graph Transform

The proof of persistence relies on the Graph Transform method.

Definition A.15 (Graph Transform). In adapted coordinates (x, y) near \Lambda_0, write the map as:

\Phi(x, y) = (A x + f(x, y), \, B y + g(x, y))

with \|A\| \le \rho_{\text{tan}}, \|B^{-1}\|^{-1} \ge \rho_{\text{norm}}, and \rho_{\text{norm}} > \rho_{\text{tan}} (spectral gap). For a Lipschitz function h: \Lambda_0 \to E^{\text{norm}}, the graph transform \Gamma(h) is defined implicitly by the condition that the graph of h is mapped to the graph of \Gamma(h):

\Phi(x, h(x)) = (x', \Gamma(h)(x'))

This yields a functional equation that, under the spectral gap, defines a contraction on a suitable function space.

Theorem A.4 (Contraction of Graph Transform). There exists a constant \kappa < 1 and a function space \mathcal{H} of Lipschitz sections such that for sufficiently small f, g (i.e., small perturbation), \Gamma: \mathcal{H} \to \mathcal{H} is a contraction with Lipschitz constant \kappa. The unique fixed point h^* defines the perturbed invariant manifold \Lambda_\varepsilon = \text{graph}(h^*).

A.2.4 Fiber Contraction and Smoothness

Theorem A.5 (Fiber Contraction Theorem — Hirsch, Pugh, Shub). Let T: E \to E be a bundle map covering a contraction f: B \to B on the base. If T is a fiber contraction (i.e., \|T|_{E_x}\| < 1 uniformly), then there exists a unique invariant section that is as smooth as T.

This theorem is used to bootstrap the C^0 fixed point h^* to C^r smoothness, establishing that the perturbed manifold inherits the smoothness of the map \Phi.

A.3 Input-to-State Stability and Contraction Theory

A.3.1 Comparison Functions

Definition A.16 (\mathcal{K} and \mathcal{KL} Functions).

· A function \gamma: \mathbb{R}_{\ge 0} \to \mathbb{R}_{\ge 0} is of class \mathcal{K} if it is continuous, strictly increasing, and \gamma(0) = 0.
· A function \beta: \mathbb{R}_{\ge 0} \times \mathbb{R}_{\ge 0} \to \mathbb{R}_{\ge 0} is of class \mathcal{KL} if for each fixed t, \beta(\cdot, t) is of class \mathcal{K}, and for each fixed s, \beta(s, \cdot) is decreasing to zero.

Definition A.17 (Input-to-State Stability — Sontag 1989). A discrete-time system x_{k+1} = f(x_k, u_k) is ISS if there exist \beta \in \mathcal{KL} and \gamma \in \mathcal{K} such that for all initial x_0 and bounded inputs u:

\|x_k\| \le \beta(\|x_0\|, k) + \gamma\left(\sup_{0 \le j < k} \|u_j\|\right)

Theorem A.6 (ISS Lyapunov Characterization — Jiang & Wang 2001). The system is ISS if and only if there exists a smooth function V: \mathbb{R}^n \to \mathbb{R}_{\ge 0}, constants \alpha_1, \alpha_2 \in \mathcal{K}_\infty, \alpha_3 \in \mathcal{K}, and \sigma \in \mathcal{K} such that:

\alpha_1(\|x\|) \le V(x) \le \alpha_2(\|x\|)

V(f(x, u)) - V(x) \le -\alpha_3(\|x\|) + \sigma(\|u\|)

A.3.2 Discrete-Time Gronwall Inequality

Lemma A.7 (Discrete Gronwall). Let \{x_k\}, \{a_k\}, \{b_k\} be nonnegative sequences satisfying:

x_k \le a_k + \sum_{j=0}^{k-1} b_j x_j, \quad k \ge 0

Then:

x_k \le a_k + \sum_{j=0}^{k-1} a_j b_j \prod_{i=j+1}^{k-1} (1 + b_i)

Proof. Define y_k = a_k + \sum_{j=0}^{k-1} b_j x_j. Then x_k \le y_k and y_{k+1} - y_k = a_{k+1} - a_k + b_k x_k \le a_{k+1} - a_k + b_k y_k. Iterating yields the bound.

Corollary A.8. If a_k = a constant and b_k = b with b \in (0,1), then x_k \le a \frac{1 - (1-b)^k}{b} + (1-b)^k x_0 \le \frac{a}{b} + (1-b)^k x_0.

A.3.3 Contraction Analysis

Definition A.18 (Contraction Metric). A dynamical system x_{k+1} = f(x_k) is contracting with respect to a metric d if there exists \rho \in [0,1) such that d(f(x), f(y)) \le \rho \, d(x, y) for all x, y.

Theorem A.9 (Contraction and Incremental Stability). If f is globally contracting with factor \rho, then all trajectories converge exponentially to a unique fixed point, and the system is incrementally stable.

A.4 Information Theory and Fisher Information

A.4.1 Basic Definitions

Definition A.19 (Entropy). For a continuous random variable X with density p(x), the differential entropy is:

H(X) = -\int p(x) \log p(x) \, dx

Definition A.20 (Mutual Information).

I(X; Y) = \iint p(x, y) \log \frac{p(x, y)}{p(x)p(y)} \, dx \, dy = D_{\text{KL}}(p(x, y) \| p(x)p(y))

Definition A.21 (Conditional Mutual Information).

I(X; Y \mid Z) = \mathbb{E}_{p(z)}[I(X; Y \mid Z=z)] = \iiint p(x, y, z) \log \frac{p(x, y \mid z)}{p(x \mid z) p(y \mid z)} \, dx \, dy \, dz

A.4.2 Fisher Information and KL Divergence

Definition A.22 (Fisher Information Matrix). For a parametric model p_\theta(x) with parameter \theta \in \mathbb{R}^m, the Fisher Information Matrix (FIM) is:

\mathcal{F}(\theta)_{ij} = \mathbb{E}_{p_\theta}\left[ \frac{\partial \log p_\theta}{\partial \theta_i} \frac{\partial \log p_\theta}{\partial \theta_j} \right]

Theorem A.10 (KL Expansion). For small \Delta\theta:

D_{\text{KL}}(p_\theta \| p_{\theta + \Delta\theta}) = \frac{1}{2} \Delta\theta^\top \mathcal{F}(\theta) \Delta\theta + \mathcal{O}(\|\Delta\theta\|^3)

Proof. Taylor expand \log \frac{p_\theta}{p_{\theta+\Delta\theta}} around \theta, using the fact that the first-order term vanishes because \mathbb{E}[\nabla_\theta \log p_\theta] = 0.

A.4.3 Log-Sobolev Inequalities

Definition A.23 (Log-Sobolev Inequality). A probability measure \mu on \mathbb{R}^n satisfies a log-Sobolev inequality with constant C > 0 if for all smooth f: \mathbb{R}^n \to \mathbb{R} with \int f^2 d\mu = 1:

\int f^2 \log f^2 \, d\mu \le 2C \int \|\nabla f\|^2 \, d\mu

Theorem A.11 (Bakry-Émery Criterion). If the Ricci curvature of a Riemannian manifold is bounded below by K > 0, then the uniform measure satisfies LSI with constant 1/K. More generally, for a measure with density e^{-V}, if \text{Hess } V \ge \rho I, then LSI holds with constant 1/\rho.

Theorem A.12 (LSI and Concentration). LSI implies sub-Gaussian concentration: for any 1-Lipschitz function F, \mu(|F - \mathbb{E}[F]| \ge t) \le 2 e^{-t^2/(2C)}.

A.4.4 CLUB Estimator

Theorem A.13 (CLUB Upper Bound — Cheng et al. 2020). For any variational distribution q_\psi(y|x), the following is an upper bound of MI:

I(X; Y) \le I_{\text{CLUB}}(X; Y) = \mathbb{E}_{p(x,y)}[\log q_\psi(y|x)] - \mathbb{E}_{p(x)p(y)}[\log q_\psi(y|x)]

Equality holds if q_\psi(y|x) = p(y|x). The gap is exactly \mathbb{E}_{p(x)}[D_{\text{KL}}(p(y|x) \| q_\psi(y|x))].

A.5 State-Space Models and Mamba Architecture

A.5.1 Continuous-Time SSM

Definition A.24 (Linear State-Space Model). A continuous-time linear SSM is:

\dot{h}(t) = A h(t) + B u(t), \quad y(t) = C h(t) + D u(t)

where h(t) \in \mathbb{R}^N is the hidden state, u(t) \in \mathbb{R}^D is input, y(t) \in \mathbb{R}^D is output.

Definition A.25 (HiPPO Initialization — Gu et al. 2020). The HiPPO matrix A is derived from Legendre polynomial approximation, with entries:

A_{nk} = -\begin{cases} \sqrt{(2n+1)(2k+1)} & n > k \\ n+1 & n = k \\ 0 & n < k \end{cases}

This initialization enables long-range memory.

A.5.2 Discretization

Definition A.26 (Zero-Order Hold Discretization). Given a step size \Delta, the discrete SSM parameters are:

\bar{A} = e^{\Delta A}, \quad \bar{B} = (\Delta A)^{-1}(e^{\Delta A} - I) \Delta B

For diagonal A, this becomes element-wise:

\bar{A}_i = e^{\Delta \lambda_i}, \quad \bar{B}_i = \frac{e^{\Delta \lambda_i} - 1}{\lambda_i} \Delta B_i

A.5.3 Selective SSM (Mamba)

Definition A.27 (Selective SSM — Gu & Dao 2023). In Mamba, parameters \Delta, B, C become input-dependent:

\Delta_t = \text{softplus}(W_\Delta u_t + b_\Delta), \quad B_t = W_B u_t, \quad C_t = W_C u_t

The state update is:

h_t = \bar{A}_t h_{t-1} + \bar{B}_t u_t, \quad y_t = C_t h_t

where \bar{A}_t = \text{diag}(e^{\Delta_t \lambda_1}, \dots, e^{\Delta_t \lambda_N}) and \bar{B}_t is computed via the ZOH formula per channel.

Theorem A.14 (Efficiency). Selective SSM can be computed in O(N D) time using parallel associative scan, enabling linear-time sequence modeling.

